The analytical performance of the optimized O-CDs/Ca@Mu sensing system was investigated using varying concentrations of doxycycline (DOX) from 1.0-35.0 μM (Fig. 3
                        ). The fluorescence restoration of O-CDs at 552 nm exhibited a concentration-dependent response, attributed to the progressive disruption of the colored complex and subsequent reduction of inner filter effects. Quantitative analysis revealed excellent linearity (R2 = 0.9985) between the relative fluorescence intensity changes and DOX concentrations, following the equation F-F0 = 4.79 [DOX] + 6.48. The method demonstrated high sensitivity with a detection limit of 325 nM, calculated using blank signal standard deviation. Compared to previously reported fluorescence-based DOX detection methods (Table 1
                        ), this label-free approach offers several advantages including simplified operation, enhanced sensitivity, and broader linear range. The dual-signal system successfully combines rapid response time with excellent selectivity, making it particularly suitable for practical DOX determination.

The detection system operates through a carefully designed coordination chemistry between DOX and the O-CDs/Ca-Mu complex. The mechanism involves three key steps: Initially, Ca2+ ions form a stable, pink-colored complex with Mu, exhibiting a characteristic absorption peak at 505 nm. This Ca@Mu complex shows partial spectral overlap with both the excitation and emission spectra of the O-CDs, resulting in suppressed fluorescence of the O-CDs. Upon introduction of DOX, the sensing mechanism proceeds through competitive binding, where DOX preferentially chelates with Ca2+ ions due to its strong metal-binding properties. This competitive binding process leads to the displacement of Mu from its Ca2+ complex, converting it to its free form. Consequently, the pink color intensity at 505 nm decreases, reducing the spectral overlap between the Ca-Mu complex and O-CDs. This reduction in spectral overlap results in the restoration of the O-CDs' orange fluorescence (Fig. 5A
                        ), providing a quantifiable signal for DOX detection (Scheme 1
                        ). The quantum yield of O-CDs was initially 23.5%. Upon the introduction of Ca@Mu, the quantum yield significantly decreased to 5.65%, confirming a quenching effect. However, after the subsequent addition of DOX, the quantum yield increased to 11.35%, suggesting a partial recovery of fluorescence according to the added amount of DOX.
